content.text: JavaScript typeof
The typeof Operator
The typeof operator returns the data type of a JavaScript variable.
content.html: The typeof operator returns the data type of a JavaScript variable.

content.text: Primitive Data Types
In JavaScript, a primitive value is a single value with no properties or methods.
content.html: In JavaScript, a primitive value is a single value with no properties or methods.

content.text: JavaScript has 7 primitive data types:
content.html: JavaScript has 7 primitive data types:

content.text: The typeof operator returns the type of a variable or an expression.
content.html: The typeof operator returns the type of a variable or an expression.

content.code_html:
typeof "John"         // Returns string
 typeof ("John"+"Doe") // Returns string
 typeof 3.14           // Returns number
 typeof 33             // Returns number
 typeof (33 + 66)      // Returns number
 typeof true           // Returns boolean
 typeof false          // Returns boolean
 typeof 1234n          // Returns bigint
 typeof Symbol()       // Returns symbol
 typeof x              // Returns undefined

content.text: Note:
In JavaScript, null is a primitive value. However, typeof returns "object".
content.html: In JavaScript, null is a primitive value. However, typeof returns "object".

content.text: This is a well-known bug in JavaScript and has historical reasons.
content.html: This is a well-known bug in JavaScript and has historical reasons.

content.text: Complex Data Types
A complex data type can store multiple values and/or different data types together.
content.html: A complex data type can store multiple values and/or different data types together.

content.text: JavaScript has one complex data type:
content.html: JavaScript has one complex data type:

content.text: All other complex types like arrays, functions, sets, and maps are just different types of objects.
content.html: All other complex types like arrays, functions, sets, and maps are just different types of objects.

content.text: The typeof operator returns only two types:
content.html: The typeof operator returns only two types:

content.code_html:
typeof {name:'John'}   // Returns object
 typeof [1,2,3,4]       // Returns object
 typeof new Map()       // Returns object
 typeof new Set()       // Returns object

typeof function (){}   // Returns function

content.text: Note:
The typeof operator returns object for all types of objects:
content.html: The typeof operator returns object for all types of objects:

content.text: You cannot use typeof to determine if a JavaScript object is an array or a date.
content.html: You cannot use typeof to determine if a JavaScript object is an array or a date.

content.text: How to Recognize an Array
How to know if a variable is an array?
content.html: How to know if a variable is an array?

content.text: ECMAScript 5 (2009) defined a new method for this: Array.isArray() :
content.html: ECMAScript 5 (2009) defined a new method for this: Array.isArray():

content.code_html:
// Create an Array
 const fruits = ["apples", "bananas", "oranges"];
Array.isArray(fruits);

content.text: The instanceof Operator
The instanceof operator returns true if an object is an instance of a specified object type:
content.html: The instanceof operator returns true if an object is an instance of a specified object type:

content.code_html:
// Create a Date
 const time = new Date();

(time instanceof Date);

content.text: Undefined Variables
The typeof of an undefined variable is undefined .
content.html: The typeof of an undefined variable is undefined.

content.code_html: typeof car;

content.text: The typeof of a variable with no value is undefined . The value is also undefined .
content.html: The typeof of a variable with no value is undefined. The value is also undefined.

content.code_html:
let car;
typeof car;

content.text: Any variable can be emptied, by setting the value to undefined .
content.html: Any variable can be emptied, by setting the value to undefined.

content.text: The type will also be undefined .
content.html: The type will also be undefined.

content.code_html:
let car = "Volvo";
car = undefined;

content.text: Empty Values
An empty value has nothing to do with undefined .
content.html: An empty value has nothing to do with undefined.

content.text: An empty string has both a legal value and a type.
content.html: An empty string has both a legal value and a type.

content.code_html:
let car = "";
typeof car;

content.text: Null
In JavaScript null is "nothing". It is supposed to be something that doesn't exist.
content.html: In JavaScript null is "nothing". It is supposed to be something that doesn't exist.

content.text: Unfortunately, in JavaScript, the data type of null is an object.
content.html: Unfortunately, in JavaScript, the data type of null is an object.

content.text: You can empty an object by setting it to null :
content.html: You can empty an object by setting it to null:

syntaxHighlighting.text: // Now value is null, but type is still an object

syntax_highlighting.text: // Now value is null, but type is still an object

content.code_html:
// Create an Object
 let person = {firstName:"John", lastName:"Doe", age:50, eyeColor:"blue"};

person = null;
// Now value is null, but type is still an object

syntax_highlighting_data.text: // Now value is null, but type is still an object

content.text: You can also empty an object by setting it to undefined :
content.html: You can also empty an object by setting it to undefined:

syntaxHighlighting.text: // Now both value and type is undefined

syntax_highlighting.text: // Now both value and type is undefined

content.code_html:
let person = {firstName:"John", lastName:"Doe", age:50, eyeColor:"blue"};

person = undefined;
// Now both value and type is undefined

syntax_highlighting_data.text: // Now both value and type is undefined

content.text: Difference Between Undefined and Null
undefined and null are equal in value but different in type:
content.html: undefined and null are equal in value but different in type:

content.code_html:
typeof undefined      // undefined
typeof null           // object

null === undefined    // false
null == undefined     // true

content.text: The constructor Property
The constructor property returns the constructor function for all JavaScript variables.
content.html: The constructor property returns the constructor function for all JavaScript variables.

content.code_html:
// Returns function Object() {[native code]}:
 {name:'John',age:34}.constructor

// Returns function Array() {[native code]}:
 [1,2,3,4].constructor

// Returns function Date() {[native code]}:
 new Date().constructor

// Returns function Set() {[native code]}:
 new Set().constructor

// Returns function Map() {[native code]}:
 new Map().constructor

// Returns function Function() {[native code]}:
 function () {}.constructor

content.text: With the constructor, you can check if an object is an Array :
content.html: With the constructor, you can check if an object is an Array:

content.code_html: (myArray.constructor === Array);

content.text: With the constructor, you can check if an object is a Date :
content.html: With the constructor, you can check if an object is a Date:

content.code_html: (myDate.constructor === Date);

typeof "John"          // Returns "string"
typeof ("John"+"Doe")  // Returns "string"
typeof 3.14            // Returns "number"
 typeof (33 + 66)       // Returns "number"
 typeof NaN             // Returns "number"
 typeof 1234n           // Returns "bigint"
 typeof true            // Returns "boolean"
 typeof false           // Returns "boolean"
 typeof {name:'John'}   // Returns "object"
 typeof [1,2,3,4]       // Returns "object"
 typeof {}              // Returns "object"
 typeof []              // Returns "object"
 typeof new Object()    // Returns "object"
 typeof new Array()     // Returns "object"
 typeof new Date()      // Returns "object"
 typeof new Set()       // Returns "object"
 typeof new Map()       // Returns "object"
 typeof function () {}  // Returns "function"
 typeof x               // Returns "undefined"
 typeof null            // Returns "object"

content.text: Note:
The data type of NaN (Not a Number) is number !
content.html: The data type of NaN (Not a Number) is number !

content.text: The void Operator

The void operator evaluates an expression and returns undefined . This operator is often used to obtain the undefined primitive value, using "void(0)" (useful when evaluating an expression without using the return value).
content.html: The void operator evaluates an expression and returns undefined. This operator is often used to obtain the undefined primitive value, using "void(0)" (useful when evaluating an expression without using the return value).

content.code: Useless link   Click me to change the background color of body to red
content.code_html:
<a href="javascript:void(0);">
  Useless link
</a>

<a href="javascript:void(document.body.style.backgroundColor='red');">
  Click me to change the background color of body to red
</a>
